  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the major aspects covered under ISO/TS 16949 Audit?",
  "response": "ISO/TS 16949, which has been superseded by IATF 16949:2016, is a globally recognized standard for quality management systems within the automotive industry. The auditing process for IATF 16949 focuses on several major aspects, including:\n\n1. **Quality Management System (QMS):** \n   - Evaluation of the overall structure and effectiveness of the QMS, including its ability to meet regulatory requirements and enhance customer satisfaction.\n\n2. **Leadership and Commitment:**\n   - Assessment of top management's role in the QMS, focusing on their commitment to quality, customer focus, and continuous improvement.\n\n3. **Customer Requirements:**\n   - Understanding and management of customer-specific requirements, ensuring these are integrated into the QMS processes.\n\n4. **Risk Management:**\n   - Processes for identifying, assessing, and managing risks related to product quality and production processes.\n\n5. **Planning and Continuous Improvement:**\n   - Review of planning processes, including quality objectives, strategies for achieving them, and mechanisms for continuous improvement.\n\n6. **Product Realization:**\n   - Evaluation of processes from design and development to production, highlighting control measures to ensure product quality and conformity.\n\n7. **Performance Evaluation:**\n   - Use of metrics and analysis to evaluate the performance of the QMS and identify areas for improvement.\n\n8. **Supplier Management:**\n   - Supplier selection, performance monitoring, and improvement processes, ensuring supplier compliance with required standards.\n\n9. **Internal Audits and Management Reviews:**\n   - Regular internal audits and management reviews to ensure QMS efficacy and alignment with strategic objectives.\n\n10. **Corrective and Preventive Action:**\n    - Processes for identifying non-conformities, determining their causes, and implementing corrective and preventive actions to avoid recurrence.\n\n11. **Training and Competence:**\n    - Ensuring all personnel involved are competent and adequately trained, with records to demonstrate this competence.\n\n12. **Documented Information:**\n    - Control and management of documents and records, ensuring the right information is available at the right time for effective operation of the QMS.\n\nThese aspects are crucial for maintaining a robust quality management system and ensuring compliance with automotive industry requirements. Audit processes are typically rigorous, aiming to ensure the highest standards are met and sustained.",
